It is never too late to make a dream come true, even if it means that you have
to make your his first parachute jump at the age of one hundred. On December
19th, Aida Gemaque Mendes, better known as Vó Iaiá (Granny Iaiá), successfully
jumped 8,000 feet through the skies of the city where she has lived since
1959, [Macapá](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macap%C3%A1), capital of the
Brazilian state of Amapá.

[![Photo br Alcinéa Cavalcante, published with
permission](https://globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
content/uploads/2009/12/0801.JPG)](http://www.alcinea.com/sem-categoria/vo-
iaia-passeando-no-ceu)

“I want to stroll in the sky, to feel a little closer to God”. Photo by
Alcinéa Cavalcante, published with permission

During the four hour wait to jump, Vó Iaiá told jokes, remembered stories of
her life and comforted her many relatives and friends who were there to
support her, guaranteeing them that she was very happy and not afraid at all.
Among the onlookers was the blogger [Alcinéa
Cavalcante](http://www.alcinea.com/sem-categoria/uma-vovozinha-muito-peralta)
[pt], who [documented the preparation](http://www.alcinea.com/sem-
categoria/momentos-antes) and the [after jump](http://www.alcinea.com/sem-
categoria/e-depois) in photos, and later interviewed the hero granny:

> Aos 100 anos, completados em novembro passado, ela dança, caminha, joga
> vôlei, basquete e futebol. “O que eu gosto mais é de dançar. Ihhhhh adoooro
> dançar”, diz com os olhos brilhando e dando uns requebros.  
>  Falta alguma coisa? Faltava. Faltava saltar de paraquedas. Peraltice que
> ela realizou ontem em Macapá. “Quero passear no céu, me sentir mais pertinho
> de Deus”, disse.
>
> […]
>
> Quando desceu, Vó Iaiá era o retrato da maior felicidade do mundo. Ergueu os
> braços para o céu e agradeceu a Deus. Deu entrevista coletiva contando que
> “foi bom demais”, que “é muito legal”, que não sentiu nenhum tantinho de
> medo, só uma “coisa estranha no ouvido por causa do vento forte” e que quer
> saltar de novo.

At 100, in November, she dances, walks, plays volleyball, basketball and
football. “What I like most is dancing. Ahhhhh I loooove dancing,” she says
wiggling, her eyes shining.  
Is there anything missing? Something was missing. She had never done a
parachute jump. A feat she performed yesterday in Macapá. “I want to stroll in
the sky, to feel a little closer to God,” she said.

